            <tr class=3D"replica" name=3D"s8">
             <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: =
16px; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">In the end, the =
bidding for the large painting played out basically as expected. One or two=
 bidders chased the work up to the well-publicized $95 million level. That =
number was so well known that when a Christie=E2=80=99s specialist tried to=
 lob in a chopped bid at $88.5 million, auctioneer <b>Adrien</b> <b>Meyer</=
b> responded to his colleague with a light-hearted over-the-shoulder quip: =
=E2=80=9CI can=E2=80=99t hear those bids.=E2=80=9D <br/><br/>Once the guara=
ntee was met, all the action came from two telephone bidders. The guarantor=
 and eventual winner was represented by <b>Alex Rotter</b>, Christie=E2=80=
=99s chairman of the 20/21 art departments. His opponent was <b>Xin</b> <b>=
Li-Cohen</b>, the house=E2=80=99s jet-setting deputy chair with strong ties=
 to China. At least one observer who watched the bidding was charmed by the=
 symmetry of Li-Cohen=E2=80=94who is married to <b>Lyor</b>
<b>Cohen</b>, a legendary music industry presence=E2=80=94bidding on the pr=
ized painting of Mica Ertegun, another glamorous, globe-trotting figure who=
 was married to a legendary music executive. (In fact, Cohen oversaw Atlant=
ic Records, which Mica=E2=80=99s husband, <b>Ahmet Ertegun</b>, co-founded,=
 and whose hits likely paid for the painting in 1968.) Li-Cohen chased the =
work all the way to $103.5 million; and, for a few moments, it seemed as if=
 she might prevail. A flurry of calculations ensued on Rotter=E2=80=99s sid=
e of the room before he jumped his bid another million above the expected n=
ext increment of $104 million, to $105 million. With that, the hammer came =
down. <br/><br/>If Rotter=E2=80=99s bidder, widely gossiped about and repor=
ted without contradiction as billionaire <b>Ken Griffin</b>, was also the t=
hird-party guarantor, the selling price was probably somewhere below the pr=
o forma $121 million a non-guarantor would have paid. (Christie=E2=80=99s n=
o longer reports net prices, as Sotheby=E2=80=99s
continues to do.) Nevertheless, the value statement had been made. The top =
price for a Magritte had moved up by<i> 50 percent</i> in two and a half ye=
ars, repricing almost everything underneath. A few lots after the gouache o=
f <i>L=E2=80=99empire des lumi=C3=A8res</i>, a slightly smaller gouache of =
a different Magritte image, <i>La recherche de l=E2=80=99absolu, </i>estima=
ted at $3 million, made $8.4 million with fees. By contrast, two other Magr=
ittes owned by Ertegun, which sold at the beginning of her sale, only made =
prices around the estimate levels. There was no Magritte bidding bump befor=
e the big <i>L=E2=80=99empire</i> painting sold. There was one after. Timin=
g really is <i>everything</i>.<br/><br/>Christie=E2=80=99s had carefully pl=
aced the Ertegun <i>L=E2=80=99empire des lumi=C3=A8res </i>as the last lot,=
 a fitting crescendo to her dedicated sale, but selling the gouache require=
d an assist. The hope was that the underbidder on the large painting would =
switch to the smaller one, but bruised feelings take
a little time to get over, and Christie=E2=80=99s would have wanted a littl=
e space for the impact of the big sale to sink in. Also, if the big paintin=
g sold to the guarantor in an anticlimactic moment, the change of sale from=
 Ertegun to various owners would act as a buffer, allowing bidders to regro=
up and rebuild momentum. <br/><br/>In the end, there were five lots placed =
between the big Magritte and its little brother, but the gouache was positi=
oned right before Christie=E2=80=99s other big lot of the evening: Ed Rusch=
a=E2=80=99s <i>Standard Station, </i>priced at $50 million but expected to =
be bid higher. In setting up the lot order, Christie=E2=80=99s both express=
ed its confidence in its ability to market both paintings and put all of it=
s eggs into one high-risk basket. The big Magritte had a belt-and-suspender=
s third-party guarantee, but the small Magritte and the Ruscha were being s=
old naked, as they say. Both the little Magritte and the big Ruscha had to =
sell well for Christie=E2=80=99s to call the
night a success=E2=80=94and make any money. <br/><br/>In the end, Christie=
=E2=80=99s didn=E2=80=99t have to worry. Close to a dozen different bidders=
 chased the <i>L=E2=80=99empire</i> gouache. Bidding started in the room fo=
r as little as $4.8 million, but quickly escalated in a relay race of biddi=
ng and counter-bidding. <b>Max Carter</b>, who had done so much to carry th=
e ball on Palmieri=E2=80=99s consignment in-house, came in at $11 million. =
There were still several bidders active at $14 million, but Li-Cohen=E2=80=
=94who=E2=80=99d come in at $12.5 million, presumably representing the unde=
r bidder on the big empire painting=E2=80=94pushed to $15.5 million. Carter=
 took one last shot, chopping his bid to $15.7 million, which signalled to =
Li-Cohen that $16 million would most likely take it. She bid that=E2=80=A6 =
and won. <br/><br/>Art auctions rarely adhere to such a tightly choreograph=
ed and cinematic script. Minutes before the sale, <b>Michel Legrand</b>=E2=
=80=99s theme to <i>The Thomas Crown Affair</i> came over the sound system,
in homage to a Magritte having been the object of Crown=E2=80=99s larcenous=
 obsession in the 1999 remake. The sale of the gouache provided the necessa=
ry subplot to bring the whole story together. <br/></td>
            </tr>
